Sugar Mills, IDBI, Maruti, Petronet: India Equity Preview

-- B y   R a j e s h   K u m a r   S i n g h
-- 
2011-03-23T01:30:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-23/sugar-mills-idbi-maruti-petronet-india-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
149.25, or 0.8 percent, to 17,988.30. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on
the National Stock Exchange advanced 0.9 percent to 5,413.85.
The BSE 200 Index increased 0.8 percent to 2,223.60.  Sugar Mills: India allowed exports of 500,000 metric tons
of sugar at a meeting of lawmakers, Vilasrao Deshmukh, minister
for rural development, said in  New Delhi  yesterday. The
government is also considering levying import tax on the
sweetener, an unidentified official said after the meeting.
Shares of  Bajaj Hindusthan Ltd. (BJH)  , the nation’s largest
producer, rose 2.6 percent to 70.45 rupees.  Balrampur Chini
Mills Ltd. (BRCM)  , the second biggest, advanced 1.6 percent
to 71.60 rupees, while  Shree Renuka Sugars Ltd. (SHRS)  , the
nation’s biggest refiner, rose 3.1 percent to 72.25 rupees.  IDBI Bank Ltd. (IDBI)  : The state-controlled lender will
provide a $120 million syndicated loan for the Meydan Heights
projects in Dubai. Meydan, Dubai’s state-owned developer of the
world’s biggest horse-racing complex, made the announcement in
an e-mailed statement yesterday. IDBI Bank shares rose 0.4
percent to 133.30 rupees.  Maruti Suzuki India Ltd. (MSIL)  : Tax payments by the
nation’s biggest carmaker fell 13 percent in the year that ends
March 31, a tax department official, who declined to be
identified before an announcement, said in New Delhi yesterday.
Shares of the company rose 3.9 percent to 1,171.95 rupees.  Petronet LNG Ltd. (PLNG)  : The company will start its
Kochi liquefied natural gas terminal on India’s west coast in
the third quarter of 2012, the company said yesterday. The first
2.5 million metric tons of annual import capacity will start
first and the second 2.5 million tons will follow in the fourth
quarter, Rajender Singh, the terminal’s senior vice president,
said yesterday at the Gastech conference in Amsterdam. The
company’s shares declined 1.1 percent to 118.35 rupees.  To contact the reporters on this story:
